    "definition": "A combination of the words for breakfast and lunch, and which is neither breakfast nor lunch, which combines some of the features of both and is served mid-morning.\n- History:\nBrunch first appeared in England at the end of the 19th century. In August 1896, the word appeared in the magazine called Punch. The magazine reported on a company breakfast by Mr. Guy Beringer of the defunct Hunter’s Weekly about a combined breakfast and lunch that was served after guests returned home from a morning of hunting. The article went on to say “To be fashionable nowadays, we much brunch.” It was not until the 1930s in the United States that the idea of brunch became popular in restaurants and hotels. Customers became know as “pilers.”"
